Approach : A number n is not prime if it is less than or equal to 1.
           For any integer starting from 2, if ğ‘–^2 is greater than n, then n is prime.
           If n is divisible by any i (i.e., n mod i = 0), then n is not prime.
   Reason : Any number ğ‘› that has a divisor must have at least one divisor less than or equal to its square root. If you check all numbers up to the square root of n and find no divisors, thereâ€™s no need to check numbers greater than the square root, as they would already have been accounted for as the complementary divisor.

Code : 
  #include <iostream>
  #include <cmath>Â 
  using namespace std;
  
  bool isPrime(int n, int i) {
  Â  Â  if (n <= 1) return false;Â 
  Â  Â  if (i * i > n) return true;Â 
  Â  Â  if (n % i == 0) return false;Â 
  Â  Â  return isPrime(n, i + 1);Â 
  }
  
  int main() {
  Â  Â  int n;
  Â  Â  cin >> n;
  Â  Â  cout << (isPrime(n, 2) ? "Prime" : "Not Prime") << endl;
  Â  Â  return 0;
  }

